post_text:
School Funding Dependent on Census Count

Dear HFAA Families,

With less than a month remaining, Oklahoma ranks 40th nationally for participation in the 2020 Census. For every uncounted resident, an estimated $17,000 in funding is lost each decade. For a family of four, that's a staggering loss of $68,000, much of it federal education funding that our kids so desperately rely on.

We want you to know how critical it is to be counted and we want to encourage you to participate in the 2020 Census if you haven't already!

https://sde.ok.gov/sites/default/files/documents/files/Census-2020_One-Sheet%20Education%20Department%5B2%5D.pdf

post_text:
Welcome back, Firehawks! It’s been the longest Spring Break ever and a strange start of the year to be sure. We have many challenges to face this year, but whether you’ll be walking through our doors each week or working from home, you are one of ours. We’ve missed you as much as you’ve missed your friends, and we’re eager to reconnect.

Tomorrow, we will see our Freshmen & Sophomores and Friday our Juniors & Seniors. For our virtual students we will continue to work with each of you and make sure you are connected and have what you need. We know we’re all in the same storm, but we recognize everyone has a different boat and different needs to weather this storm.

Thank you for your patience and support. We’re a community school, and we couldn’t do this without our community!
Mr. Schmelzenbach @ Harding Fine Arts Academy

Dear HFAA Families & Friends:

As you may have heard, the State Superintendent of Public Instruction, Joy Hofmeister, announced yesterday that she will propose a Continuous Learning Plan to the State Board of Education on Wednesday for their approval. The plan to be presented is intended to complete the school year for Oklahoma students without reopening school buildings during the COVID-19 pandemic.

We are sharing this information with you in advance, however, so that we can begin to prepare together. This is not what we had hoped for, but we understand this recommendation is in the best interest of everyone’s health, which is our greatest priority. If approved, this sadly also means that…

Harding Fine Arts Academy is at Harding Fine Arts Academy.
March 23 at 12:15 AM · Oklahoma City, OK ·

Dear HFAA Families,

Keeping our students healthy and fed during this unprecedented crisis is important. Over Spring Break, HFAA has been working through the process of becoming a meal site during the COVID-19 closures, and we are pleased to now be listed on Hunger Free Oklahoma’s website as one of the city-wide student meal providers beginning this Tuesday morning, 3/24 at 7:30am.

WHO can participate?
Any student age 18 or younger, regardless of where they are enrolled.
Students must be present unless they are sick.
If you are a senior with HFAA and already 19, don’t let that stop you. Come get your meals!

WHERE can families get meals for students?
HFAA will be serving on the south side of…

post_text: Dear HFAA Community, Out of an abundance of caution, HFAA Classes and After-events are cancelled Friday, March 13. We will update families with any changes in our schedule beyond tomorrow. For clarity, we have no reported case of COVID-19 or contract with anyone who has been diagnosed. This action is a community response out of an abundance of caution. We expect to receive additional guidance from the OK State Dept of Education tomorrow and will keep you updated with more detailed information over the coming days.

Dear Harding Fine Arts Families,

If you haven’t noticed this week’s weather forecast, you might want to look at Wednesday. Oklahoma’s weather has a long history of unpredictable changes that can start with a warm sunny day in the morning and shift to North Dakota by noon. This can quickly impact classes, dismissal times, after-school events, and our disdain for groundhogs.

With the chance for winter weather, we need to anticipate the chance for poor road conditions, and we want to make sure our students, families, and staff are safe and aware of HFAA's Winter Weather Plan.

Here are some Frequently Asked Questions:

1) How will we know if HFAA is closed or shortening hours due to weather?

post_text:
Firehawks! We have some wonderful news from Oklahoma Thespian Festival that was held over this last weekend!

Evie Hughes and Emerson Hacker were cast in the Oklahoma Playworks production!

Josiah Billingslea was selected as a Best in Show performer, and will perform his solo musical theatre piece for the whole festival!

Ian Wehrenberg auditioned for colleges, and was called back for 17 colleges overall!

15 students competed in IEs, and 5 received rewards/recognition! Duncan Rumbaugh, Abigail Manners, Josiah Billingslea, Lily Voth, and Annie Brown received superior ratings on their IE competition pieces and are eligible to compete at International Thespian Festival in July!

Please please please offer these kiddos your biggest congrats on Monday! They’ve worked so hard and were all winners based on their sportsmanship and amazing attitudes. We easily had the best behaved, most respectful students at the entire festival. #firehawkpride

Firehawks,

Some weeks are longer than others and this week has been a week both disheartening and inspiring. As most of you know, there was a particularly hateful social media post this week about our transgender students. HFAA has a long and strong history of inclusion, and a faculty and staff who actively work to support, build leadership, and provide resources for our LGBTQ students.

To our LGBTQ community: You are more than our students; you are tightly woven into our community, our mission, and our hearts. You each have faces, dreams for your futures, and deep intrinsic value.

To our student body: What you post on social media has real consequences. You can either use your voice to…

post_text: Hydration: As we’ve moved into different spaces this year, one challenge is the need to add water fountains on floors that don’t have any. We’ve installed a water fountain/bottle filler on the 3rd floor (thank you Mr. Sapp!), but the moving of water fountains has been more problematic than expected. In an effort to quickly solve this, and save Mr. Campbell’s back from carrying water coolers to keep students hydrated, we have three new water fountains/bottle fillers arriving this week and our plumber is assessing the best place (water & drain) to install them. For now, the goal is to place two on the 3rd floor and one on the 2nd floor to reflect where the majority of students are during the day (there is already a water fountain on the 1st floor). We look to begin installation this week, but we should have at least one new fountain/bottle filler per floor when we come back from this upcoming holiday weekend!

For now, the goal is to place two on the 3rd floor and one on the 2nd floor to reflect where the majority of students are during the day (there is already a water fountain on the 1st floor). We look to begin installation this week, but we should have at least one new fountain/bottle filler per floor when we come back from this upcoming holiday weekend!

post_text:
It’s Official!

Every August for the past 95 years the sun’s early morning rays have crested the horizon and washed over this dragon. Across nearly a century, tens of thousands have walked under its watchful eye, but most have never seen it. This morning was different though. I took the time at sunrise to join this mythical creature by the front doors and greet first light together. I watched as the rays met its eye and moved down its face, reigniting again the fire inside. This August 1st marks the turning of a page, the beginning of a new chapter for the rock to which it clings so tightly. Yesterday the Harding School Building officially changed hands, so I intentionally began this day… More

Dear HFAA,
I want to give you a quick update on where we’re at with the building. As you know, the district put the Harding Building up for public bid, along with five other buildings. Today at 2pm was the deadline for most of them, including Harding. The HFAA Foundation submitted a bid proposal for the building and six of our board members were there with me for the bid opening. HFAA’s proposal was officially the only bid submitting!

The next steps will be a review of our proposal by the District’s legal team, then from there the OKCPS administration will evaluate and make a recommendation. Ultimately, the OKCPS Board must approve the sale of the Harding Building to HFAA.

We believe HFAA’s…
